04087nam a22005655i 9780773597884DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735978847 a10.1515/97807735978842doi  a(DE-B1597)657048  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aB832bM14 2015 7aPHI0200002bisacsh04a144/.3223  aCI 11102rvk1 aMaddalena, Giovanni, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Philosophy of Gesture :bCompleting Pragmatists' Incomplete Revolution /cGiovanni Maddalena. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tAnti-Kantianism and Pragmatist Characteristics -- tPeirce’s Incomplete Synthetic Turn -- tA New Paradigm for Reasoning -- tA New Tool: Complete Gesture -- tGestures and Creativity -- tFigural and Narrative Identity -- tWriting as Complete Gesture -- tGesture, Morality, Education -- tConclusions and Further Studies -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn everyday reasoning - just as in science and art - knowledge is acquired more by "doing" than with long analyses. What do we "do" when we discover something new? How can we define and explore the pattern of this reasoning, traditionally called "synthetic"? Following in the steps of classic pragmatists, especially C.S. Pierce, Giovanni Maddalena's Philosophy of Gesture revolutionizes the pattern of synthesis through the ideas of change and continuity and proposes "gesture" as a new tool for synthesis. Defining gesture as an action with a beginning and an end that carries on a meaning, Maddalena explains that it is a dense blending of all kinds of phenomena - feelings and vague ideas, actual actions, habits of actions - and of signs - icons, indexes, and symbols. When the blending of phenomena and signs is densest, the gesture is "complete," and its power of introducing something new in knowledge is at its highest level. Examples of complete gestures are religious liturgies, public and private rites, public and private actions that establish an identity, artistic performances, and hypothesizing experiments. A departure from a traditional Kantian framework for understanding the nature and function of reason, The Philosophy of Gesture proposes an approach that is more attuned with our ordinary way of reasoning and of apprehending new knowledge.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAct (Philosophy). 0aIdentity (Philosophical concept). 0aPragmatism. 70(DE-601)1061959640(DE-588)4047046-5aPragmatismus2gnd 70(DE-601)1062002590(DE-588)4045791-6aPhilosophie2gnd 70(DE-601)1062881990(DE-588)4026482-8aIdentität2gnd 70(DE-601)10630464X0(DE-588)4023277-3aHandlung2gnd 70(DE-601)1238159400(DE-588)4308398-5aAktgPhilosophie2gnd 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Pragmatism.2bisacsh1 aZalamea, Fernando, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359788440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773597884423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773597884/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles